&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;How it works&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/images/monochord_5.png&quot; alt=&quot;alt text&quot; title=&quot;monochord pic 5&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The electromagnets are driven by pulse-width modulated signals. The concept here is different from the  well-kown E-bows, which are using a feedback-loop. There are a few benefits from using a direct PWM excitation :&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;the string enters much faster in resonance&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;the string can vibrate at potentially any of its resonance mode or any combination of modes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The downside being of course that the frequencies must be known by the system, hence the dedicated tuning knobs.
There is one fine-tuning potentiometer per harmonic. They allow a slight detuning of each PWM wave, in order to accomodate for the string natural inharmonicity.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The string itself can be tuned via two pegs, one for coarse and one for fine tuning.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The instrument needs to be powered by an external 15V batterie / AC adapter.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

